                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d100">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/459a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Straus</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-08-19T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 19, 1935—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>336. French Ambassador informs us that on August 14 the French replied to British
                    memorandum of August 2 on future naval construction. <pb facs="0197" n="95"
                        xml:id="pg_95"/> Ambassador stated French Foreign Office was going to inform
                    you of the sense of its reply. Ambassador further stated qualitative proposals
                    in memorandum were in general acceptable to French Government subject to
                    acceptance by Americans and Japanese; that any program for new building should
                    be for longer than 5-year period. If Foreign Office has not informed you of
                    French reply, you might say we were informed of its intention to do so and thus
                    endeavor to obtain as much information as possible with regard to French
                    reply.</p>
                <p>Repeat this telegram and your reply to London for Embassy’s information.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
